    <fr:title text="Comparing Normal Forms">Comparing Normal Forms</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Quiz</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:ol><html:li><html:strong>Is a formula that is DNF also in NNF?</html:strong></html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>How can we check the satisfiability of a formula in DNF?</html:strong></html:li></html:ol>
 
   
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" expanded="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>11</fr:month><fr:day>22</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Solution</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:ol><html:li>Yes. As we are restricted to the same set of connectives in both DNF and NNF, and since DNF also only applies negations to literals, any formula in DNF is also in NNF.</html:li>
    <html:li>A formula in DNF is satisfiable if at least one of its clauses is satisfiable. Since each clause is a conjunction of literals, a clause is satisfiable if none of its literals contradict each other (i.e., it does not contain both a variable and its negation). Thus, to check the satisfiability of a DNF formula, we can examine each clause individually and see if there exists at least one clause where all literals can be true simultaneously.</html:li></html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
